title: Model
text:
Define Linear Model and Fit


Code
X = get_dummies(df[['bill_length_mm', 'species', 'sex']], drop_first = True)
y = df['body_mass_g']

model = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)

title: Model
section: Using Cross-Validation to Judge Model Performance
text:
Using Cross-Validation to Judge Model Performance


Code
#prep code
set.seed(1234)
df <- palmerpenguins::penguins
df<-na.omit(df)

Penguins_folds <- vfold_cv(df, v = 5)
lm_spec <- linear_reg() %>%   
  set_mode("regression") %>%   
  set_engine("lm")


#cross-validating
lm_spec %>%   
  fit_resamples(body_mass_g ~ bill_length_mm+as.factor(species)+as.factor(sex), resamples = Penguins_folds, 
                metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq)) %>%   
  collect_metrics()


# A tibble: 2 × 6
  .metric .estimator    mean     n std_err .config

title: About
text:
Dataset
The dataset (seen below) is a well-known collection of penguin measurements and information on adult foraging penguins near Palmer Station, Antartica. This dataset is commonly used to learn/demonstrate different modeling techniques. Here, it is being used to demonstrate the capabilities of DevOps to create a website product. For an in depth look at the Penguins data set, refer to the Penguins Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) tab!


Code
palmerpenguins::penguins


# A tibble: 344 × 8
   species island    bill_length_mm bill_depth_mm flipper_length_mm body_mass_g
   <fct>   <fct>              <dbl>         <dbl>             <int>       <int>
 1 Adelie  Torgersen           39.1          18.7               181        3750
 2 Adelie  Torgersen           39.5          17.4               186        3800
 3 Adelie  Torgersen           40.3          18                 195        3250
 4 Adelie  Torgersen           NA            NA                  NA          NA
 5 Adelie  Torgersen           36.7          19.3               193        3450
 6 Adelie  Torgersen           39.3          20.6               190        3650
 7 Adelie  Torgersen           38.9          17.8               181        3625
 8 Adelie  Torgersen           39.2          19.6               195        4675
 9 Adelie  Torgersen           34.1          18.1               193        3475
10 Adelie  Torgersen           42            20.2               190        4250
# ℹ 334 more rows
# ℹ 2 more variables: sex <fct>, year <int>


Variable Specifics:

Species: Different species of observed penguins(Adelie, Chinstrap, Gentoo)
Island: Different islands on the Palmer Archipelago (Biscoe, Dream, Torgersen)
Bill_length_mm: Bill length in millimeters
Bill_depth_mm: Bill depth in millimeters
Flipper_legnth_mm: Flipper length in millimeters
Body_mass_g: body mass in grams
sex: penguin sex (male or female)
year: year study was conducted (2007,2008,2009)


Model
The model used is a simple linear regression. The predictor variables are bill_length_mm, sex, and species. The response variable is body_mass_g.
Meet the Author
Hi! My name is Taylor McManus. I am from Columbia, MD and I am currently a Junior at the US Air Force Academy (USAFA). This project was done as an introductory into DevOps in accordance with the USAFA Math 378 Course.

References
This website was created based on the labs in the chapters 1-6 of Alex K. Golds DevOps for Data Science textbook. Additionally, substantial help was provided by ChatGPT, Dr. Jessica Hauschild, and Dr. Brianna Hitt. DevOps for Data Science (do4ds.com)

title: Penguins Exploratory Data Analysis
section: Penguin Size vs Mass by Species
text:
Penguin Size vs Mass by Species









In general, this graph demonstrates that the species predictor has a strong relationship with the bill_length_mm and body_mass_g. For Adelie penguins, there seems to be bill_length_mm and body_mass_g values on the lower end suggesting that the Adelie species is typically a smaller type of penguin. The Chinstrap seems to demonstrate longer bill_length_mm but similar body_mass_g meaning that these penguins are similar size to Adelie penguins but with a proportionally longer bill. Finally, the Gentoo penguins show generally higher body_mass_g than both species and bill_length_mm similar to the Chinstrap species. This tells us that likely these are the biggest penguin species of thr three and have bill legnths proportionally closer to the Adelie penguins.

title: Penguins Exploratory Data Analysis
section: Penguin Size vs Mass by Sex
text:
Penguin Size vs Mass by Sex









The line of best fit for the two sexes are relatively parallel demonstrating that the overall proportion of bill_length_mm and body_mass_g have similar results between male and female penguins. Looking at the individual data points, it seems that, on the extreme ends of body_mass_g, males tend to lie in the high zone and females in the low. In the center of the body_mass_g range, there is a good mix. This demonstrates that sex may not be the only delineating factor in correlated body_mass_g. As seen above, the interplay of species also has a big play in the mass of a penguin. In terms of bill_length_mm, there seems to be an even spread across the range for both sexes. Overall, this graph shows a weaker relationship between bill_length_mm and body_mass_g, and sex in comparison to the relationship show above with bill_length_mm and body_mass_g, and sex.
